{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a42a74cf-fa27-42a2-866f-c38e469fe756","content":"Update these three files:\n\n**1. `*.csproj`** — change the target framework:\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\n**2. `global.json`** — pin the new SDK:\n```json\n{ \"sdk\": { \"version\": \"11.0.100\" } }\n```\n\n**3. `Dockerfile`** — update base images:\n```dockerfile\nFROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:11.0 AS base\nFROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:11.0 AS build\n```\n\nAfter editing, run:\n```bash\ndotnet restore\ndotnet build\n```\n\nAlso check for any NuGet packages with version `10.0.*` (e.g., `Microsoft.AspNetCore.*`, `Microsoft.Extensions.*`) in your `.csproj` and bump those to their `11.0.*` equivalents.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1ef2cd3e-d79a-442b-b5d8-c7ca9f4ed781","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to update their .NET project from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a straightforward question about version bumps across their config files. I don't need to search any codebase — I can answer directly.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"1427:BBE67:5DE3E39:6997D79:69EC1B71"},"id":"b538f0fd-2eac-4f39-986a-176a4ec9fc67","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:40:08.503Z","parentId":"f9d82d94-bb89-4ea3-8a27-e693ad405522"}
